tickets.description:
In using the TEI XSL to generate slides, it sensibly uses item/@n in any ordered list if present as the number for that item.

But what it doesn't do is carry on from a new number and number successive items sequentially:

&lt;p&gt; And some more chapters on a new slide:
&lt;list type="ordered"&gt;
&lt;item n="13"&gt; Names, Dates, People, and Places&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt; Tables, Formulæ, and Graphics&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt; Language Corpora&lt;/item&gt;
...&lt;/list&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

The first item will be numbered 13, the second 2, the third 3, etc.

What I'm suggesting is that once the numbering has been changed, the default action should be to carry on from that number.  I recognise that this means someone who wants to preserve erroneous numbering as printed '1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 6' would need to put in each number rather than just the second 3 and the 4.  It just seems a more intuitive default to me the other way round.

In http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/TC.html the Guidelines provide critical apparatus examples from various Chaucer manuscript witnesses with the phrase 'Experience though noon Auctoritee' and similar.

In one example we have:
&lt;rdg wit="\#La"&gt;Experiment thogh noon Auctoritee&lt;/rdg&gt;
in another we have:
&lt;rdg wit="\#La" type="orthographic"&gt;thouh&lt;/rdg&gt;
and another:
&lt;rdg wit="\#La"&gt;thouhe&lt;/rdg&gt;
and 
&lt;rdg wit="\#La"&gt;thouh&lt;/rdg&gt;

While I recognising these could be demonstrating different editorial choices \(and if so this should be flagged to the reader\), rather than the text of the actual manuscript, it does appear inconsistent since the examples are purporting to indicate realistic MS witnesses.

Obviously this is a trivial bug of low priority, I post it here only as a reminder that when this chapter is revised, it should be proofread for consistency.

In the verse chapter we have:

&lt;body&gt;
&lt;div n="I" type="book"&gt;
&lt;div n="1" type="canto"&gt;
&lt;lg n="I.1.1" type="stanza"&gt;
&lt;l&gt;A Gentle Knight was pricking on the plain&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;l&gt;Y cladd in mightie armes and silver shielde,&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;/lg&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;

Instantly followed by:

&lt;body&gt;
&lt;div n="I" type="book"&gt;
&lt;div n="I.1" type="canto"&gt;
&lt;div n="I.1.1" type="stanza"&gt;
&lt;l&gt;A noble knight was pricking on the plain&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;l&gt;Ycladd in mightie armes and silver shielde,&lt;/l&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;


Is he noble or Gentle?  Enquiring minds want to know.

Converting these EEBO Holinshed texts throws up what I think is a bug.

They have a paragraph, which ends, followed by a &lt;trailer&gt;FINIS&lt;/trailer&gt; followed by a:
&lt;trailer&gt;
&lt;figure rend="block"&gt;
&lt;figDesc&gt;printer's or publisher's device&lt;/figDesc&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/trailer&gt;

But &lt;figure&gt; is not allowed inside &lt;trailer&gt;.   &lt;graphic/&gt; is allowed, but provides no way to supply a description. \(Why doesn't &lt;graphic/&gt; allow a &lt;desc&gt; child? Presumably because in those cases you should use &lt;figure&gt;?\)



&lt;trailer&gt; allows macro.phraseSeq which doesn't contain model.inter which is what provides &lt;figure&gt; to the likes of a &lt;p&gt; since model.inter is allowed in macro.paraContent.   Sebastian notes that &lt;table&gt; may suffer from the same problem, and that if &lt;formula&gt; is allowed, then &lt;table&gt; should be since one could use a table in a phrase-level context.


Suggested solution:

1\) Change content model of &lt;trailer&gt; to be macro.paraContent, or explicitly allow &lt;figure&gt; inside it.  Another possibility would be to change figure to make it model.graphicLike so it would appear anywhere a graphic could...but that might have other unforeseen effects.  Maybe needs more thinking out, but one should be able to provide a figure with a figDesc in or after a trailer.
2\) Allow a &lt;desc/&gt; child of &lt;graphic&gt;.  One should never be able to provide a graphic without the possibility of something from which to generate @alt text in HTML.

-James

When a new customised element is created within ODD as belonging to a specific custom namespace \(e.g. &lt;cch:oList&gt;\) there isn't at present an appropriate element to record examples of usage for such custom element, as &lt;egXML&gt; accepts only elements from the TEI namespace and &lt;eg&gt; element accepts only texts. 

Therefore neither:
&lt;exemplum&gt;
&lt;egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"&gt;
&lt;cch:oList&gt;
&lt;item&gt;First Item&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Second Item&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Third Item&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/cch:oList&gt;
&lt;/egXML&gt;&lt;/exemplum&gt;

and 

&lt;exemplum&gt;
&lt;eg&gt;
&lt;cch:oList&gt;
&lt;item&gt;First Item&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Second Item&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Third Item&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/cch:oList&gt;
&lt;/eg&gt;
&lt;/exemplum&gt;

are valid.

I suggest one of the following solutions:

1\. enlarge &lt;egXML&gt; to accept any piece of well formed XML

2\. allow &lt;eg&gt; to accept any piece of well formed XML

3\. create a new element \(e.g. &lt;egXMLcustom&gt;\) to accept any piece of well formed XML

