A typical WWP file has 2-4 &lt;idno&gt; elements. Two in the &lt;publicationStmt&gt; that refer to the file itself in formal terms. E.g., from our edition of Aphra Behn's \_The Amorous Prince\_:
&lt;idno type="WWP"&gt;TR00241&lt;/idno&gt;
&lt;idno type="URL"&gt;http://www.wwp.brown.edu/texts/behn.amorous.html&lt;/idno&gt;
These are always present. And then, 99% of files have 1 or 2 &lt;idno&gt;s in the &lt;sourceDesc&gt; to give the identification of the source document in somewhat formal terms, e.g. a library shelf number. E.g., from our edition of Joanna Cartwright's \_The Petition of the Jews\_:
&lt;idno type="LT"&gt;Thomason Tract E.537\(17\)&lt;/idno&gt;
&lt;idno type="Wing"&gt;C695&lt;/idno&gt;
Hope this helps.

