Actually, I'm not sure of my recommendation any more.  I could read this recommendation three different ways, assuming footnote number 68:

a. &lt;ptr target="\#foo" n="68"/&gt; at the point of the footnote reference, pointing to &lt;note place="bottom" anchored="true" xml:id="foo"&gt;\[text of note\]&lt;/note&gt;

b. &lt;ref target="\#foo"&gt;68&lt;/ref&gt; at the point of the footnote reference, pointing to &lt;note place="bottom" anchored="true" xml:id="foo"&gt;\[text of note\]&lt;/note&gt;

c. &lt;note place="bottom" anchored="true" target="\#foo" n="68"&gt;\[text of note\]&lt;/note&gt;, pointing \(the other way\) to &lt;ptr xml:id="foo"/&gt; at the point of the footnote reference

Furthermore, it's not clear whether the n= attribute should be used on both the pointer and the &lt;note&gt; element.  I guessed in my examples.

At next release, added the following warning text:

&lt;p&gt;The meanings of concepts such as sex, nationality, or age are
highly culturally-dependent, and the encoder should take particular
care to be explicit about any assumptions underlying their usage of
them. For example, when recording personal age in different cultures,
there may be different assumptions about the point from which age is
reckoned. A statement of the practice adopted in a given encoding may
usefully be provided in the &lt;gi&gt;editorialDecl&lt;/gi&gt; element discussed
in &lt;ptr target="\#HD53"/&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;


stuart yeates wrote:
&gt; The thing that I struggled with here was
&gt; 
&gt; \(a\) the example in the standatd makes no sense to me, and
&gt; 
&gt; \(b\) the Western, Japanese, Chinese or Korean distinction is not a 
&gt; question of dimension \(or att.dimensions.attributes\) but a question of 
&gt; where you measure from \(conception, birth or New Year\).
&gt; 
&gt; I highly recommend the following book for the calendar calculations 
&gt; involved in this kind of thing. His early work is packaged with emacs:
&gt; 
&gt; http://www.amazon.com/Calendrical-Calculations-Millennium-Edward-Reingold/dp/0521777526
&gt; 
&gt; \[my copy is an earlier edition\]
&gt; 
&gt; What I would like to see is an example in the TEI standard that used 
&gt; something like:
&gt; 
&gt;      &lt;encodingDesc&gt;
&gt;        &lt;editorialDecl&gt;
&gt;          &lt;p&gt;Ages are marked up in the Western age reckoning.&lt;/p&gt;
&gt;          ...
&gt;        &lt;/editorialDecl&gt;
&gt;        ...
&gt;      &lt;/encodingDesc&gt;
&gt; 
&gt;      ...
&gt; 
&gt; \[ ... some example of &lt;age&gt; ...\]
&gt; 
&gt; cheers
&gt; stuart
&gt;

I think David and Lou are correct, Kevin’s suggestion of putting multiple BCP 47 language tags into a single xml:lang= attribute is a bad idea. \(At least, until such time as W3C explicitly says it’s OK.\) However, his original concern still stands, and \(despite David and Lou’s assertions\) it is not clear to me that &lt;langUsage&gt; along with a global xml:lang= are sufficient for his use case.

Imagine that Kevin is trying to convert a large legacy textbase written in KHML to TEI. In KHML no attempt was made to indicate the natural language of particular chunks of text. However, each metadata record contains a “myLangs” field, which contains 1 to 20 BCP 47 tags, which indicate every language that occurs in the text of the document.

So given a KHML text that has "en de la" in its “myLangs” field, what should Kevin do to convert to TEI? He can’t automatically put xml:lang= on individual elements in the text, and he can’t afford to pay someone to read his large corpus and put them on by hand.

There are two other obvious possibilities. The first is to use &lt;textLang&gt;. This has three disadvantages:
1\. It’s part of msdescription module, not header module
2\. It is not permitted inside &lt;teiHeader&gt; except as a child of an msElement of some sort
3\. It intends, if not requires, that the languages present be divided into one “main” and zero or more “other” \(a distinction KHML does not make\).

The other possibility is to use &lt;langUsage&gt; for this purpose:
&lt;langUsage&gt;
&lt;language ident="en"/&gt; &lt;language ident='de'/&gt; &lt;language ident="la"/&gt;
&lt;/langUsage&gt;

However, I am uncomfortable with this use. While the Guidelines do not explicitly prohibit this, there is an implication that the presence of a langUsage/language/@ident implies that there exist elements with xml:lang= values that match the value of the ident=.

This could be fixed, of course, by putting a sentence and perhaps example in the Guidelines that license this usage of &lt;langUsage&gt;. But I think before that is done, Council should seriously consider Kevin’s suggestion \(or a variation thereof\).

I have two suggestions:
1\) Putting &lt;textLang&gt; inside of &lt;langUsage&gt; instead of a series of &lt;language&gt; elements. I.e., 
element langUsage \{ \( language+ | textLang \) \}
\(This does not address the mainLang= vs. otherLangs= problem.\)
OR
2\) Putting a langs= attribute on &lt;langUsage&gt; to be used instead of a series of &lt;language&gt; elements. I.e. something like the following.
&lt;content&gt;
&lt;rng:zeroOrMore xmlns:rng="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0"&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="language"/&gt;
&lt;/rng:zeroOrMore&gt;
&lt;/content&gt;
&lt;constraintSpec scheme="isoschematron" ident="langUsage"&gt;
&lt;constraint&gt;
&lt;s:rule context="tei:langUsage"&gt;
&lt;s:report test="@langs and child::tei:language"&gt; Natural
languages used within the text should be listed
briefly on the &lt;att&gt;langs&lt;/att&gt; attribute or, for
more detailed encoding \(like recording the
percentage of each language used, or when the
passages in particular languages have been indicated
with &lt;att&gt;xml:lang&lt;/att&gt;\), using &lt;gi&gt;language&lt;/gi&gt;
child elements, but not both. &lt;/s:report&gt;
&lt;/s:rule&gt;
&lt;/constraint&gt;
&lt;/constraintSpec&gt;
&lt;attList&gt;
&lt;attDef ident="langs"&gt;
&lt;datatype minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="unbounded"&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="data.language"/&gt;
&lt;/datatype&gt;
&lt;/attDef&gt;
&lt;/attList&gt;

Either of these suggestions has the benefit of differentiating the two cases \(mentioning the languages used, vs providing detailed information\) very explicitly right up front. One can imagine that when doing language processing of large corpora it is far more efficient to be able to look for the existence of /TEI/teiHeader/profileDesc/langUsage/language/@ident rather than for /TEI/text\[@xml:lang\]|/TEI/text//\*\[@xml:lang\].

I think Kevin is right. The Guidelines should have an example of a non-inline encoding of a note where there is a footnote reference in the text \(and perhaps also in the note itself\). Something like
&lt;ref xml:id="a51" type="noteAnchor"&gt;&amp;\#x2075;&amp;\#x00B9;&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;\!-- ... --&gt;
&lt;note target="\#a51" type="footnote"&gt;&lt;label&gt;&amp;\#x2075;&amp;\#x00B9;.&lt;/label&gt; See also … &lt;/note&gt;
That said, I think it is also important that the Guidelines make clear that this is not the only way of handling this situation, that it is perfectly reasonable \(and conformant TEI\) to leave the little superscript digits \(or other marker\) out and use &lt;anchor&gt; \(or whatever\) and &lt;note&gt; without the actual marker being explicitly represented as content. This is a particularly useful approach if either
a\) generated output does not need to be particularly faithful to the exact characters used as a marker, or
b\) the processes to which the text will be put do not involve the footnote markers at all \(e.g., calculating the average number of syllables per sentence in main text vs annotation\)

tickets.description:
In the "Rhyme" section of the Guidlines chapter on verse \(VE-Verse.xml\#VERH\):

&lt;p&gt;Non-rhyming lines within such a group may be represented using a
hyphen or an x, as in the following example:
&lt;egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"&gt;
&lt;\!-- example needed --&gt;
&lt;/egXML&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

Obviously, an example is needed.

There are many places where &lt;graphic/&gt; is allowed in which you might want the rendered version of that &lt;graphic/&gt; to contain a descriptive metadata about it the image in question. i.e. the information you might want to supply to an @html:alt attribute when rendering.  Currently there is no good way I can see to do this?  Certainly figDesc exists when describing figures, but nothing similar exists for &lt;graphic/&gt;

A use case for this is &lt;graphic/&gt; as a child of &lt;char&gt;, especially when you have multiple &lt;graphic/&gt;s at that point.  e.g. you have the character as rendered by one font or another version of that font, or another font entirely.
&lt;char xml:id="whatever"&gt;
&lt;desc&gt;Punctus Elevatus&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;graphic url="punct-el-JR.png"&gt;&lt;desc&gt;Punctus Elevatus as rendered by the Junicode Regular Font&lt;/desc&gt;&lt;/graphic&gt;
&lt;graphic url="punct-el-JI.png"&gt;&lt;desc&gt;Punctus Elevatus as rendered by the Junicode Italic Font&lt;/desc&gt;&lt;/graphic&gt;
&lt;graphic url="punct-el-And.png"&gt;&lt;desc&gt;Punctus Elevatus as rendered by the Andron Web Scriptor Font&lt;/desc&gt;&lt;/graphic&gt;
&lt;/char&gt;

It seems silly to have to move this burden to processing and to substring-matching to then test everthing after the second - but before the .png to see which font it is, to create the equivalent of an @html:alt attribute.  Since all html:img elements should have @alt attributes to comply with web accessibility guidelines, I think we need a way to store the text that would be used to make this @alt attribute at the site of the &lt;graphic/&gt; element.  Other alternatives include a @desc attribute or similar but that is a step backwards into the icky free-text attribute days. Another possiblity would be to allow macro.xtext inside graphic and state that this was a description of the graphic \(not a transcription\).

-James

posts.text:
Council solved my initial use-case for this, by allowing &lt;figure&gt; inside &lt;char&gt;.  However, that was only one use-case.  Another one is the use of &lt;graphic/&gt; elsewhere, for example inside &lt;facsimile&gt; where you want to provide different graphics and give descriptions of them.
i.e.
&lt;surface&gt;
&lt;graphic url="http://foo.com/abc1234.jpg"/&gt;
&lt;graphic url="http://foo.com/abc1234a.jpg"/&gt;
&lt;/surface&gt;

The remote images are potentially on a server out of the user's control, and so they can't rename these 'hi-res.jpg' and 'low-res.jpg', &lt;graphic/&gt; is not a member of att.typed so you can't categorise them that way.  Moreover you might want to provide a description of the graphic for use as html:@alt text. ...exactly the suggestion made in the original request.  While the solution \(figure in char\) did solve my immediate problem, it doesn't solve the underlying one.

So I've re-opened this ticket and set it back to amber.

Potential solutions are:

a\) add graphic to att.typed, and allow an optional model.descLike content \(exactly on the model of and basically same reasons as with &lt;gap/&gt;\) 
b\) allow figure inside facsimile/surface \(which seems worse to me\).

-James

tickets.description:
There are 22 &lt;valDesc&gt;s for attributes of datatype data.word. Of these, four incorrectly imply that \*any\* character can be used, when in fact there are entire classes of Unicode characters that are not eligible. In particular, characters that fall into the category of marks, separator, or other cannot be used. \(List attached.\) These &lt;valDesc&gt;s are for:
n= of att.global
rend= of att.global
sortKey= of &lt;term&gt;
value= of &lt;metSym&gt;

\(In addition those for sortKey= of att.entryLike and loc= of &lt;app&gt; were problematic, but these were such easy fixes, I’ve gone ahead and changed “any” to “a” in the tagdocs at revision 6665.\)

Hi Lou,

The following passage in section v.1 \(http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/SG.html\#SG11\) has been inherited from the original intro to SGML:
&gt;
&gt; Three characteristics of XML distinguish it from other markup languages:
&gt;
&gt;    1. its emphasis on descriptive rather than procedural markup;
&gt;    2. its notion of documents as instances of a document type;
&gt;    3. its independence of any one hardware or software system.
&gt;
I suspect the comparison is really no longer true, since at a minimum XML shares these features with other SGML-based languages. Perhaps the thing to do is remove the comparative aspect and just state these as strengths of XML, i.e. "XML has three main strengths:"

posts.text:
Revised wording:

&gt;XML has three highly distinctive advantages: 
&lt;list type="ordered"&gt;
&lt;item&gt;it places emphasis on descriptive rather than
procedural markup;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;it distinguishes the concepts of syntactic correctness and of
&lt;term&gt;validity&lt;/term&gt; with respect to a &lt;term&gt;document type definition&lt;/term&gt;;&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;it is independent of any one hardware or software
system.&lt;/item&gt;&lt;/list&gt;

