tickets.description:
The content models of &lt;classSpec&gt;, &lt;constraintSpec&gt;, &lt;elementSpec&gt;, &lt;moduleSpec&gt;, and even &lt;schemaSpec&gt; are loose enough to permit no child elements. That is, in an ODD file
&lt;elementSpec ident="killMe" mode="delete"/&gt;
is valid, but
&lt;macroSpec ident="data.killMe" mode="delete"/&gt;
is not.

I note, however, that Vesta \(I think version 1.0.9, but it's hard to tell\) processes empty &lt;macroSpec&gt; elements correctly.

posts.text:
&gt; I have changed the content model accordingly ... as 7035

Excellent, thank you.

&gt; It would be a good idea at some future revision to enforce a rule
&gt; that an empty \*Spec element is permitted only if the case where
&gt; @mode="delete".

It is pretty important to permit empty \*Spec elements where @mode='use' \(or whatever it ends up being called\), too. This permits easier management of customization ODDs. E.g., consider the following snippet \(best viewed w/ monospace typeface\):
&lt;\!-- begin module for chapter 5, “Representation of Non-standard Characters and Glyphs” --&gt;
&lt;moduleRef key="gaiji"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="char"        mode="use"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="charDecl"    mode="use"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="charName"    mode="use"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="charProp"    mode="delete"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="g"           mode="use"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="glyph"       mode="delete"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="glyphName"   mode="delete"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="localName"   mode="delete"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="mapping"     mode="use"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="unicodeName" mode="delete"/&gt;
&lt;elementSpec module="gaiji" ident="value"       mode="use"/&gt;

Adding or deleting an element becomes trivial. \(Snippet generated by my ODDframe.xslt, then hand-tweaked.\)

tickets.description:
I observed some inconsistencies with regards to the documentation of the &lt;summary&gt; element:
-chapter 10 of the TEI Guidelines, "Manuscript Description" only describes it as child of
-&lt;msContents&gt;: 10.6 Intellectual Content -- &lt;http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/MS.html\#msco&gt;
-&lt;typeDesc&gt;: 10.7.2.1 Writing -- &lt;http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/MS.html\#msphwr&gt;
-OTOH 1: the definition of &lt;summary&gt; \(&lt;http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-summary.html&gt;\) formally defines it as child of:
-&lt;decoDesc&gt;
-&lt;handDesc&gt;
-&lt;history&gt;
-&lt;layoutDesc&gt;
-&lt;msContents&gt;
-&lt;typeDesc&gt;
-OTOH 2: the prose definition of &lt;summary&gt; \(&lt;http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-summary.html&gt;\) reads:
"contains a brief summary of the intellectual content of an item, provided by the cataloguer"
...and only points to the discussion of &lt;msContents&gt; at 10.6 Intellectual Content \(&lt;http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/MS.html\#msco&gt;\)

It seems that the prose definition of &lt;summary&gt; is out of sync with its formal definition.

In an ODD, when using &lt;valItem&gt; elements to define a list of allowed values for a given attribute, @ident is used to contain an allowed value, e.g. &lt;valItem ident="value1"/&gt;.  @ident is of type data.name \(i.e., an XML name\).

The problem with this is that it is perfectly possible one might be dealing with an attribute that requires a data.pointer, so one might wish to write
&lt;valList mode="replace" type="closed"&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="\#value1"/&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="\#value2"/&gt;
&lt;/valList&gt;
or you might want to allow other types of attribute values, such as:
&lt;valItem ident="London and Paris"/&gt;
or
&lt;valItem ident="9abc"/&gt;
which are all invalid in the current schema.

Whilst I believe every other element within the tagdocs module that uses @ident from att.identified requires an XML name, this is not the case with &lt;valItem&gt;, so might I suggest that this element has a separate implementation of @ident of type "text".

posts.text:
Yes. Something like the following. Note that ident= is still present on &lt;valItem&gt;, so that it can be, well, identified. But software would choose the actual list of possible values by selecting one child &lt;val&gt; \(using its “match the language” algorithm\), falling back to ident= if there were no child &lt;val&gt;s. \(Note that I’ve used BP as if it were a measurement in the following, but in fact it is two separate measurements — systolic and diastolic. Also note that I can’t find my Spanish medical dictionary, so the translations are suspect. And my Spanish is not good enough to provide &lt;desc&gt;s.\)

&lt;elementSpec ident="measure" mode="change"&gt;
&lt;attList&gt;
&lt;attDef ident="commodity" mode="replace"&gt;
&lt;datatype minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"&gt;
&lt;rng:ref name="data.enumerated"/&gt;
&lt;/datatype&gt;
&lt;valList&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="HR"&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="en"&gt;heart rate&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="es"&gt;tarifa corazón&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;desc xml:lang="en"&gt;measured via auscultation or ECG; not to be confused with
pulse rate&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="PR"&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="en"&gt;pulse rate&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="es"&gt;tarifa pulso&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;desc xml:lang="en"&gt;measured via palpation at a peripheral pulse point; not to
be confused with heart rate&lt;/desc&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="RR"&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="en"&gt;respiratory rate&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="es"&gt;tarifa respiración&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="BP"&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="en"&gt;blood pressure&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="es"&gt;presión arterial&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;valItem ident="temp"&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="en"&gt;temperature&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="es"&gt;temperatura&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
&lt;/valList&gt;
&lt;/attDef&gt;
&lt;/attList&gt;
&lt;/elementSpec&gt;

It makes perfect sense to me.  The principle \(as already stated\) is that the application should produce a schema based on the value in &lt;val&gt;, not @ident.  However, @ident is retained to avoid breaking apps that assume \(as stated in the Guidelines\) that "All documentation elements in ODD have a canonical name, supplied as the value for their ident attribute" and also as a fallback value. If it were being redesigned from scratch, there might be a better way of doing it, but this solution shouldn't cause any headaches as long as it's carefully documented.

As regards languages, I think you're confusing &lt;gloss&gt; with &lt;altIdent&gt;.  In the example, the &lt;valItem xml:lang="es"&gt; is the equivalent of what would normally be &lt;altIdent xml:lang="es"&gt;.  Of course there's no urgent need to retain &lt;altIdent&gt;s as there is for @ident, but a careful user might include one as a fallback.

So essentially, both @ident and &lt;altIdent&gt; are superseded by valItem/val elements.  However, valItem/@ident is not "language-independent" but inherits from previous @xml:lang atttributes, though whether applications properly respect this when generating schemas and documentation I don't know.  Taking Syd's example for reference, it might have been written like this:

&lt;TEI xml:lang="en" ...&gt;
...
&lt;valItem ident="HR"&gt;
&lt;val&gt;heart rate&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;val xml:lang="es"&gt;tarifa corazón&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
...
&lt;/TEI&gt;

as the equivalent of:

&lt;TEI xml:lang="en" ...&gt;
...
&lt;valItem ident="HR"&gt;
&lt;altIdent xml:lang="es"&gt;TC&lt;/val&gt;
&lt;/valItem&gt;
...
&lt;/TEI&gt;

Comments on this from MJD follow:
\---
I would handle this as follows:

&lt;support&gt;Most leaves are:
&lt;dimensions type="leaves" scope="most" unit="mm"&gt;
&lt;height scope="range" min="295" max="300"&gt;295-300&lt;/height&gt;
&lt;width quantity="205"&gt;205&lt;/width&gt;
&lt;/dimensions&gt;
With the following exceptions:
&lt;locus from="1" to="13"&gt;1-13&lt;/locus&gt;
&lt;dimensions&gt;
&lt;height extent="range" min="315" max="320"&gt;315-320&lt;/height&gt;
&lt;width&gt;205&lt;/width&gt;
&lt;/dimensions&gt;
&lt;\!-- --&gt;
&lt;/support&gt;

It depends a bit on what's meant by "All other leaves". One could also
put the exceptions in a &lt;list&gt;, thus linking the &lt;locus&gt; and
&lt;dimensions&gt; elements.

The alternative would be:

&lt;dimensions type="leaf" scope="range"&gt;
&lt;height min="70" max="320"&gt;70-320&lt;/height&gt;
&lt;width min="123" max="252"&gt;123-252&lt;/width&gt;
&lt;/dimensions&gt;

in other words taking the highest and lowest heights and widths.
Nobody's going to like that solution, though.

A @range attribute would be nice, or if @scope could take an actual
range \(in addition to all, most and scope\). The following is legal, but
messy:
&lt;dimensions scope="ff.1-13"&gt;
&lt;height extent="range" min="315" max="320"&gt;315-320&lt;/height&gt;
&lt;width&gt;205&lt;/width&gt;
&lt;/dimensions&gt;

On the whole, I'm not partial to the idea of allowing @from, @to and
@scheme on dimensions.

