tickets.description:
Transforming this small sample with the xml/tei/stylesheet/fo2/tei.xsl from TEI-XSL
&lt;TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"&gt;
&lt;text&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;note&gt;&lt;hi&gt;&lt;lb/&gt;&lt;/hi&gt;&lt;/note&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;/TEI&gt;
leads to an fo that is not conformant to the FO specification,

The resulting FO looks something like this:
&lt;footnote&gt;
&lt;inline font-size="7pt" vertical-align="super"&gt;1&lt;/inline&gt;
&lt;footnote-body&gt;
&lt;block end-indent="0pt" start-indent="0pt" text-align="start"
font-style="normal" text-indent="1em" font-size="8pt"&gt;&lt;inline
font-size="7pt" vertical-align="super"&gt;1&lt;/inline&gt;
&lt;inline&gt;&lt;block/&gt;&lt;/inline&gt;&lt;/block&gt;
&lt;/footnote-body&gt;
&lt;/footnote&gt;

The problem is that the FO specification does not allow this\(block inside inline inside foonote\).
http://www.w3.org/TR/xsl/\#fo\_inline
"An fo:inline that is a child of an fo:footnote may not have block-level children. An fo:inline that is a descendant of an fo:leader or of the fo:inline child of an fo:footnote may not have block-level children, unless it has a nearer ancestor that is an fo:inline-container."

As a result when the FO is processed with Apache FOP it fails with a message like this:
net.sf.saxon.trans.XPathException: org.apache.fop.fo.ValidationException: Error\(4/-1\): fo:block is not a valid child element of fo:inline:  An fo:inline that is a descendant of an fo:leader or fo:footnote may not have block-level children, unless it has a nearer ancestor that is an fo:inline-container.

Section 3.3 says to capture a sequential label in the @n on a div.  However, it's not clear what to do if instead of "III", your source says "Chapter III".  Encoding as:

&lt;div1 n="Chapter III" type="part"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;Chapter III: It Awakes&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;/div1&gt;

would go against the datatype of @n.

posts.text:
If do want to have an @n, I would see two possible strategies:
\- take what actually correpond to the numbering in the text as content, like you suggest \(since we put plain text in an attribute it should be untagged and as a consequence should be kept in the &lt;head&gt;\)
&lt;div1 n="Chapter III" type="part"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;Chapter III: It Awakes&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;/div1&gt;
\- use an actual numarical value mimicing the relative value \(3 here\):
&lt;div1 n="3" type="part"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;Chapter III: It Awakes&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;/div1&gt;
The division hierarchy can then do the trick of recomposing a full absolute numbering if needed. Should we then have  @unit to indicate what type of object we are counting in this case?

the definition of @points has been changed to
