Each of the sentences in which these elements are introduced begins "When . . . " and continues after the blocked-in element name + short description. The fact that the element name + short description is itself a complete sentence ending with a period makes chaos of the larger sentence into which it is embedded. Elsewhere in the Guidelines, this problem is avoided by constructing the larger sentence in such a way as to be coterminous with the element name + definition. I suggest that the relevant bit of HD-Header.xml be edited to read:

&lt;p&gt;When the header describes a text derived from some pre-existing
TEI-conformant or other digital document, it may be simpler to use the
following element, which is designed specifically for documents derived from texts
which were &lt;soCalled&gt;born digital&lt;/soCalled&gt;:
&lt;specList&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="biblFull"/&gt;
&lt;/specList&gt;
For further discussion, see section &lt;ptr target="\#HD31"/&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When the module for manuscript description is included in a schema,
this class also makes available the following element:
&lt;specList&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="msDesc"/&gt;
&lt;/specList&gt;
This element enables the encoder to record very detailed information about
one or more manuscript or analogous sources, as further discussed in
&lt;ptr target="\#MS"/&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

As currently written, the Guidelines say that refsDecl may include refsDecl, cRefPattern, and refState. As it may not, in fact, contain itself, either the way the list is introduced must be changed or the one &lt;specList&gt; must be divided into two. I'd suggest the latter option as easier:

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;gi&gt;refsDecl&lt;/gi&gt; element is  used to
document the way in which any standard referencing scheme built into
the encoding works. 
&lt;specList&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="refsDecl"/&gt;
&lt;/specList&gt;
It may contain either a series of prose paragraphs or the following specialized elements:
&lt;specList&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="refsDecl"/&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="cRefPattern"/&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="refState"/&gt;
&lt;/specList&gt;

As currently written, this section doesn't contain a specDesc for &lt;textClass&gt;. I recommend the following:

&lt;div type="div3" xml:id="HD43"&gt;&lt;head&gt;The Text Classification&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The second component of the core &lt;gi&gt;profileDesc&lt;/gi&gt; element is the
&lt;gi&gt;textClass&lt;/gi&gt; element. 
&lt;specList&gt;
&lt;specDesc key="textClass"/&gt;
&lt;/specList&gt;
This element is used to classify a text
according to one or more of the following methods:

posts.text:
Adding more information for my own benefit, trying to understand this ticket:

The text of the Guidelines says this:

"The value of the class attribute should specify the identifier used for the appropriate classification within a taxonomy element, defined in the classDecl element of the TEI Header \(2.3.6 The Classification Declaration\), as shown here:

&lt;classDecl&gt;
&lt;taxonomy&gt;
&lt;\!-- --&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="law"&gt;
&lt;catDesc&gt;Laws&lt;/catDesc&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;\!-- --&gt;
&lt;/taxonomy&gt;
&lt;/classDecl&gt;"

But the attribute description in the msItemStruct definition says this:

"class	identifies the text types or classifications applicable to this item
Status 	Optional
Datatype 	

data.code

Values 	One or more codes, each of which is used as the identifier for a text classification element supplied in the TEI Header textClass element."

The same issue would seem to be present in the case of msItem. The fix would presumably be to change "used as the identifier for a text classification element supplied in the TEI Header textClass element" to something like "as supplied by a &lt;category&gt; element within a taxonomy element, defined in the classDecl element of the TEI Header".

But should there be only one pointer in @class, or "one or more"? The Guidelines text says "the identifier", but the attribute definitions in the elementSpecs show:

&lt;datatype minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="unbounded"&gt;
&lt;ref xmlns="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/1.0" name="data.pointer"/&gt;
&lt;/datatype&gt;

There are two problems here: the use of the word "classification" rather than specifying the actual element type which should be indicated; and the ambiguity as to whether @class can indicate multiple targets or a single one. \(The latter is the same as the uncertainty noted elsewhere about @target on &lt;catRef&gt;\) . At rev \#9614 I have also reworded the passage following the "Jonsbok" example as follows:

The value used for the &lt;att&gt;class&lt;/att&gt; attribute
in this example  points to a
&lt;gi&gt;category&lt;/gi&gt; element with the identifier &lt;code&gt;law&lt;/code&gt;, which
defines the classification  concerned. Such &lt;gi&gt;category&lt;/gi&gt; elements
will typically appear within 
a &lt;gi&gt;taxonomy&lt;/gi&gt; element,  within the &lt;gi&gt;classDecl&lt;/gi&gt;
element of the TEI Header \(&lt;ptr target="\#HD55"/&gt;\) as
in the following example:
&lt;egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"&gt;
&lt;classDecl&gt;&lt;taxonomy&gt;
&lt;\!-- --&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="law"&gt;
&lt;catDesc&gt;Legislation&lt;/catDesc&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;category xml:id="war"&gt;
&lt;catDesc&gt;Military topics&lt;/catDesc&gt;
&lt;/category&gt;
&lt;\!-- --&gt;
&lt;/taxonomy&gt;&lt;/classDecl&gt;
&lt;/egXML&gt;
More than one classification may apply to a single item. Another text,
concerned with legislation about military topics might thus be
specified as follows:
&lt;egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" xml:lang="non"&gt;
&lt;msItem class="\#law \#war"&gt;
&lt;\!-- details of the item here --&gt;
&lt;/msItem&gt;
&lt;/egXML&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

The use of @version is entirely confused and contradictory, I am afraid. The Guidelines source says 
&lt;TEI version="5.0"&gt;
which seems mildly meaningless, compared to the one you cite at http://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/examples-TEI.html which says &lt;TEI version="1.2.0"&gt;
We also have
Source/Specs/teiCorpus.xml:      &lt;teiCorpus version="5.2"&gt;

But these are only \_examples\_, so should they be updated automagically?

All the other uses of @version are dates on translations, I think?

