If I put a &lt;constraintSpec&gt; that has only  a child &lt;sch:report&gt; \(i.e., no &lt;sch:rule context=&gt;\)  into an &lt;attDef&gt; child of &lt;elementSpec&gt;, the default context= in the extracted Schematron is the element, not the attribute.

E.g.: \[If this turns out to be too hard to read, I'll put the same in an attached file.\]

&lt;elementSpec ident="platypus" mode="add"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;classes mode="replace"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;memberOf key="model.nameLike.agent"/&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/classes&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;attList&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;attDef ident="bill"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;datatype&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;rng:value&gt;duck&lt;/rng:value&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/datatype&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;constraintSpec scheme="isoschematron" ident="silly-test"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;constraint&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;sch:report test="true\(\)"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;My context is &lt;sch:value-of select="."/&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/sch:report&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/constraint&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/constraintSpec&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/attDef&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/attList&gt;
&lt;/elementSpec&gt;

results in

&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;pattern id="platypus-constraint-silly-test"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;rule context="tei:platypus"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;report test="true\(\)"&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;My context is &lt;value-of select="."/&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/report&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/rule&gt;
&amp;\#xA0;&amp;\#xA0;&lt;/pattern&gt;

Now, I don’t know that this is wrong. The documentation provides no help AFAIK. It says only that “the &lt;pattern&gt; and &lt;rule&gt; containers should then be generated automatically.” \(And there is no &lt;att&gt;context&lt;/att&gt; in all of the Guidelines.\) But either …

a\) It’s right, and the documentation should make very clear that the default context= is the ancestor element being defined \(platypus\), not the parent attribute being defined \(@bill\)
b\) the default context= should be the the attribute alone \(@bill\) \(and the documentation should make this clear, but it is probably what is expected, anyway\)
c\) the default context= should be the parent attribute being defined when on the ancestor element being defined \(platypus/@bill\) \(and the documentation should make this clear\). This is probably the most reasonable, but immediately begs the question what happens if the current &lt;attDef&gt; is a descendant of a &lt;classSpec&gt;, not an &lt;elementSpec&gt;?

I don’t think it matters very much which solution TEI chooses, but it needs to pick 1 and document the heck out of it to avoid confusion.

Consider the following:

&lt;head&gt;1 Zur Entstehung der &lt;hi rend="smcap"&gt;Philosophischen 
Untersuchungen&lt;/hi&gt;
&lt;note n="8" place="foot"&gt;Zu Textauszeichnungen und 
Siglen siehe die Legende.&lt;/note&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;note n="9" place="foot"&gt;Zu  Textauszeichnungen und Siglen siehe die Legende.&lt;/note&gt;

Whe n converting to HTML the first &lt;note&gt; gets rendered inline, while the second gets placed at the foot of the page
This cannot be right.

There are a number of occurences in TCP ECCO texts of &lt;list&gt; inside &lt;signed&gt;. I'd like to change the content model
of &lt;signed&gt; to be macro.paraContent instead of macro.phraseSeq. This makes sense, as &lt;signed&gt; is a sibling of &lt;p&gt;
and a child of &lt;div&gt;

Example:
&lt;closer&gt;
&lt;signed&gt;Sign'd and Seal'd,
&lt;list&gt;&lt;item&gt;John Bull,&lt;/item&gt;&lt;item&gt;Nic. Frog.&lt;/item&gt;&lt;/list&gt;
&lt;/signed&gt;
&lt;/closer&gt;

posts.text:
@Martin, I'm not sure that's a correct use of &lt;geo&gt; though, is it? According to the element spec, &lt;geo&gt; defines "any expression of a set of geographic coordinates, representing a point, line, or area on the surface of the earth", so an appropriate way to define a polygon made up of multiple points would not be one &lt;geo&gt; per point, but a single geo containing an expression like:

&lt;geo&gt;x y, x1 y1, x2 y2, x3 y3, ...&lt;/geo&gt;

And I don't think Scott's use-case--a single location that can be defined both by GPS and by OS coords--would be marked as two locations, but as two competing &lt;geo&gt;s within a single &lt;location&gt;.

Having said that, I don't particularly object to making &lt;location&gt; part of att.declaring as well, if people have a use case for it. I can certainly imagine cases unlike that of GPS vs OS, where the two sets of coords really do define different kinds of location, rather than just two notations with identical referrent.

@Lou: I think you're right about my usage, but every example in the Guidelines shows only a point, with the exception of this one, which chooses to use a different namespace to represent an area:

&lt;geo&gt;
&lt;gml:Polygon&gt;
&lt;gml:exterior&gt;
&lt;gml:LinearRing&gt; 45.256 -110.45 46.46 -109.48 43.84 -109.86 45.8 -109.2
45.256 -110.45 &lt;/gml:LinearRing&gt;&lt;/gml:exterior&gt;&lt;/gml:Polygon&gt;
&lt;/geo&gt;

In your opinion, why does &lt;location&gt; permit multiple &lt;geo&gt;s?

Martin,

I think I disagree. If you have 5 competing coordinates for Camelot, then you have 5 locations. Let's say we didn't have &lt;geo&gt; but just an address-like description using &lt;placename&gt;, &lt;country&gt;, &lt;region&gt;, etc.  \(As per the examples on the location reference page in fact\).

You wouldn't say:
&lt;location&gt;
&lt;placename&gt;Winchester&lt;/placename&gt;
&lt;region&gt;Hampshire&lt;/region&gt;
&lt;placename&gt;Cadbury Castle&lt;/placename&gt;
&lt;region&gt;Somerset&lt;/region&gt;
&lt;/location&gt;

You'd say:
&lt;location&gt;
&lt;placename&gt;Winchester&lt;/placename&gt;
&lt;region&gt;Hampshire&lt;/region&gt;
&lt;/location&gt;
&lt;location&gt;
&lt;placename&gt;Cadbury Castle&lt;/placename&gt;
&lt;region&gt;Somerset&lt;/region&gt;
&lt;/location&gt;

That reads a lot more clearly to me at least. And if that is what makes sense whith placename and region, then the same must hold true for &lt;geo&gt;

-James

tickets.description:
Using current version of Roma, if I rename an element from its page \(e.g., http://www.tei-c.org/Roma/startroma.php?mode=changeElement&element=abbr&module=core\), an empty ns= attribute is added to the &lt;elementSpec&gt;, thus generating a schema that has the element in question not only with a new local name \(desired\) but in no namespace \(very bad\).

This does \*not\* happen if I rename the element from the module tab \(e.g., http://www.tei-c.org/Roma/startroma.php?mode=changeModule&module=core\)

So, to generate this problem:
\* http://www.tei-c.org/Roma/
\* Build schema; start
\* save; Modules; core; abbr
\* Change Name -&gt; "abbreviation" ; save
\* Save Customization
=&gt; &lt;elementSpec module="core" ident="abbr" mode="change" ns=""&gt;
&lt;altIdent&gt;abbreviation&lt;/altIdent&gt;
&lt;/elementSpec&gt;
\* Schema =&gt;
tei\_abbr = element abbreviation \{
where it should have
tei\_abbr = element ns1:abbreviation \{

