tickets.description:
Dear Sebastian,

generating an ePub with OxGarage from http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/opensource/downloads/texts/tei/1999.04.0074.xml, I found that the titlepageback.html \(“Information about this book”, which is automatically generated\) has the following issues:

IMHO the title in “Title statement” should be in italics.

Different names in &lt;respStmt&gt; aren't separated by commas. That is:

&lt;respStmt&gt;
&lt;resp&gt;Prepared under the supervision of&lt;/resp&gt;
&lt;name&gt;Lisa Cerrato&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;name&gt;William Merrill&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;name&gt;Elli Mylonas&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;name&gt;David Smith&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;/respStmt&gt;

is translated as:

Prepared under the supervision of: Lisa Cerrato William Merrill Elli Mylonas David Smith

I guess that the final dot is also missing.

And regarding the source, the information is the following \(for that book\):

— Syntax of Classical Greek from Homer to Demosthenes Basil L. Gildersleeve New York American Book Company Date: 1900

Not sure whether the dash is necessary there, but there should be dots or comma separating the different fields. “Date: ” should be also removed.

Many thanks for your excellent work,


Pablo

posts.text:
I interpret it as that the &lt;fDecl/&gt; declares to which data category the &lt;f/&gt; should be equivalent. Just like the &lt;fDecl/&gt; does that for the type the f value should have. If that role is better suited in TEI for &lt;equiv/&gt; then that could be the proper construct to use. However, it could lead to inconsistencies between the FDS and FSR mechanisms:

Given the following FSD:

&lt;fsDecl type="WordForm"&gt;
&lt;fDecl
name="writtenForm"&gt;
&lt;equiv uri="http://www.isocat.org/datcat/DC-1836"/&gt;
&lt;vRange&gt;&lt;vNot&gt;&lt;string/&gt;&lt;/vNot&gt;&lt;/vRange&gt;
&lt;/fDecl&gt;
&lt;fDecl
name="grammaticalNumber"&gt;
&lt;equiv uri="http://www.isocat.org/datcat/DC-1298"/&gt;
&lt;vRange&gt;&lt;vAlt&gt;
&lt;symbol value="singular"&gt;
&lt;equiv uri="http://www.isocat.org/datcat/DC-1387"/&gt;
&lt;/symbol&gt;
…
&lt;/vAlt&gt;&lt;/vRange&gt;
&lt;/fDecl&gt;
&lt;/fsDecl&gt;

and FSR

&lt;fs type="WordForm"&gt;
&lt;f name="writtenForm"&gt;
&lt;string&gt;clergyman&lt;/string&gt;
&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;f name="grammaticalNumber"&gt;
&lt;symbol value="singular"/&gt;
&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;/fs&gt;

this FSR and FSD combination should be equivalent to

&lt;fs type="WordForm"&gt;
&lt;f name="writtenForm" dcr:datcat="http://www.isocat.org/datcat/DC-1836"&gt;
&lt;string&gt;clergyman&lt;/string&gt;
&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;f name="grammaticalNumber" dcr:datcat="http://www.isocat.org/datcat/DC-1298"&gt;
&lt;symbol value="singular" dcr:datcat="http://www.isocat.org/datcat/DC-1387"/&gt;
&lt;/f&gt;
&lt;/fs&gt;

Of course any tool interpreting the FSD can make this transition from &lt;equiv/&gt; to @dcr:\*, but is it really needed? Introducing &lt;equiv/&gt; would touch maybe more then wanted, e.g., in my example I also used &lt;equiv/&gt; to express the data category equivalence for the singular symbol. As FSR and FSD share &lt;symbol/&gt; &lt;equiv/&gt; would also become part of the FSR. The same is true the other way around @dcr:\* is available for &lt;symbol/&gt; in the FSR so also in the FSD. In my view it would be strange to use &lt;equiv/&gt; in one part of the FSD and @dcr:\* in another part ...

Just my 2 cents ...

@Lou: The idea for @corresp came from a posting by one L. Burnard:

&lt;http://listserv.brown.edu/archives/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind1204&L=TEI-L&D=0&P=63546&gt;

If you've changed your mind and would like to suggest something else, please do. In the meantime, there's a clear need for guidance about how to do this, and we do need to provide something. The addition lays out the use-cases, and provides suggestions; I'm happy to replace the suggestions with better ones, but we do need something in there.

I've added the missing hash.

tickets.description:
1\. A list is created in MS Word 2010 using list styles from the Style Pane and the DOCX document is transformed to TEI P5. In the result TEI P5 XML document an ordered list from MS Word 2010 is transformed as unordered list, including nested lists:

&lt;list type="unordered"&gt;
&lt;item&gt;One
&lt;list type="unordered"&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Two&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Three&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/list&gt;
&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;item&gt;Four&lt;/item&gt;
&lt;/list&gt;

2\. A list is nested in other list. Both lists are created using the list button in the main menu.  In the result TEI P5 XML document the nesting is lost.


You can see some examples and images here:

http://www.oxygenxml.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=19&t=7209&p=22794\#p22794

In the example given for msItemStruct I recognised that the encoding of the finalRubric contains uses of 'expan' which in my understanding should be 'ex' \(expan containing whole words/phrases while ex contains parts of words?\):

Present: &lt;finalRubric&gt;EXPLIC&lt;expan&gt;IT&lt;/expan&gt; EXPO&lt;lb/&gt;SITIO APOCALIPSIS QVA&lt;expan&gt;M&lt;/expan&gt; EXPOSVIT DOM&lt;lb/&gt;NVS APRINGIUS EP&lt;expan&gt;ISCOPU&lt;/expan&gt;S. DEO GR&lt;expan&gt;ACI&lt;/expan&gt;AS AGO. FI&lt;lb/&gt;NITO LABORE ISTO.&lt;/finalRubric&gt;

Should read: &lt;finalRubric&gt;EXPLIC&lt;ex&gt;IT&lt;/ex&gt; EXPO&lt;lb/&gt;SITIO APOCALIPSIS QVA&lt;ex&gt;M&lt;/ex&gt; EXPOSVIT DOM&lt;lb/&gt;NVS APRINGIUS EP&lt;ex&gt;ISCOPU&lt;/ex&gt;S. DEO GR&lt;ex&gt;ACI&lt;/ex&gt;AS AGO. FI&lt;lb/&gt;NITO LABORE ISTO.&lt;/finalRubric&gt;

If this is really considered "wrong" other occurences would be in the examples for rubric.

posts.text:
Actually, I made a mistake in diagosing the problem. There is a way to have the start attribute refer to a non-TEI element, as follows:

&lt;schemaSpec ident="testsvg3" start="TEI svg\_svg"&gt;
\[...\]
&lt;moduleRef prefix="svg\_" url="../svg11.rng"/&gt;
&lt;/schemaSpec&gt;

Basically by adding the prefix attribute to the import and then referrencing the desired element explicitly. I'm going to add an addendum zip file that contains a working example. Run make and it will create schemas that allow TEI and svg as start elements.

So the problem is not quite what I thought. However, the TEI documentation is definitely sending users down the wrong path. And I'd say that the solution above is on the obscure side of things.

Sebastian, rather than perhaps update the bug report myself to reflect what I just found, I'll let you decide which direction this bug report should go and make whatever changes you see fit.

