Did you apply the same XSLT stylesheet on the input XML?

Here are a couple of suggestions for rendering the MathML both in PDF and XHTML:

1\) For the PDF output in the XSL:

stylesheet/fo2/figures.xsl

in the XSL template:

&lt;xsl:template match="tei:formula"&gt;

replace &lt;wrapper&gt; with &lt;instream-foreign-object&gt;. 
PDF generation using Apache FOP will correctly render the equation after this.

2\) For XHTML in:

stylesheet/xhtml2/figures.xsl

replace calls to:

&lt;xsl:copy-of select="m:math"/&gt;

with calls to:

&lt;xsl:apply-templates select="mml:math" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" mode="copyMathML"/&gt;

and add two more XSL templates at the end of the stylesheet:

&lt;xsl:template match="\*\[namespace-uri\(\)='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'\]" mode="copyMathML"&gt;
&lt;xsl:element name="\{local-name\(\)\}" namespace="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;
&lt;xsl:apply-templates select="node\(\) | @\*" mode="copyMathML"/&gt;
&lt;/xsl:element&gt;
&lt;/xsl:template&gt;

&lt;xsl:template match="node\(\) | @\*" mode="copyMathML"&gt;
&lt;xsl:copy&gt;
&lt;xsl:apply-templates select="node\(\) | @\*" mode="copyMathML"/&gt;
&lt;/xsl:copy&gt;
&lt;/xsl:template&gt;

From what we tested for DITA HTML output, HTML with MathML embedded works fine as long as there is no prefix defined on the MathML elements. That's the solution we have in place for DITA anyway.

